  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Acute Joint Response - Ukraine</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Active conflict is ongoing in and around Eastern Ukraine since 2014, but over the past months tensions between Russia and Ukraine have increased significantly. This has resulted in a Russian invasion of Ukraine in the early hours of Feb 24. Russia has attacked Ukraine by air, land and sea, threatening the lives and livelihoods of many people. OCHA reports at least 550 civilian casualties (OCHA, 1/3), but the real number is expected to be much higher and to increase further. Infrastructure has also been affected: houses, water systems, power supply and road networks have been damaged, and people in active conflict areas are seeking shelter underground. Prices have increased drastically, and there is a shortage of basic supplies and services, amongst others food, water and health care.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Activities are tailored to the specific needs of the people directly affected by the conflict, supporting both IDPs and families remaining home. Caritas will provide assistance to all conflict affected people, but special attention is given to women and children, elderly and people with disabilities (PWD), as well as IDPs, large families, families run by single parents, and children alone. Women and children are often travelling without the adult men of the family, who have to be available for the army, increasing their protection risk. For elderly and PWD it is more difficult to flee the active conflict areas and they may be forced to stay.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The main objective of the project is to provide basic emergency assistance to most vulnerable people, affected by the conflict.</narrative>
  </description>
